{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533157"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:33:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:33:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14760"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14760"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.13,0.04,0.69,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7451"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58449"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7451"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14760"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43865"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1367"},{"type":"tags","id":"3646"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18230"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58449"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with several non-healing ulcers on her arms that developed over the past three months. She recently returned from six months of humanitarian work in rural Sudan. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are three well-circumscribed ulcers with raised borders on her forearms. A skin biopsy reveals amastigotes within macrophages, confirming cutaneous leishmaniasis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely mode of transmission in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct contact with infected dogs","Soil exposure","Person-to-person contact","Sandfly bite","Contaminated water exposure"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with cutaneous leishmaniasis acquired during travel to an endemic area. \u003Cem\u003ELeishmania\u003C/em\u003E parasites are transmitted through the bite of infected female phlebotomine sandflies. The characteristic presentation includes painless ulcers with raised borders that develop weeks to months after exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESandfly bites\u003C/strong\u003E are the only natural mode of transmission for leishmaniasis. The parasites are transmitted when an infected female sandfly takes a blood meal. The promastigote form of the parasite is injected into the skin, where it is taken up by macrophages and transforms into the amastigote form.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Edirect contact with infected dogs\u003C/strong\u003E is not a mode of transmission, dogs are important reservoir hosts for certain species of \u003Cem\u003ELeishmania\u003C/em\u003E. The parasite must still be transmitted via a sandfly vector.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContaminated water exposure\u003C/strong\u003E is not a mode of transmission for leishmaniasis. This might be confused with other parasitic diseases such as schistosomiasis which can be acquired through water contact.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerson-to-person contact\u003C/strong\u003E does not occur with leishmaniasis. While very rare transmission through shared needles or blood transfusion has been reported, direct transmission between humans does not occur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESoil exposure\u003C/strong\u003E is not a mode of transmission for leishmaniasis. This might be confused with other infections such as cutaneous larva migrans or mycetoma which can be acquired through soil contact.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevention of leishmaniasis focuses on avoiding sandfly bites through the use of insect repellents, protective clothing, and bed nets. Control of reservoir hosts and vector control are also important public health measures in endemic areas.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Leishmaniasis is transmitted by the bite of infected female sandflies.","Dogs and rodents are important reservoir hosts for leishmaniasis.","Human-to-human transmission of leishmaniasis does not occur directly."],"references":["de Vries HJC, Schallig HD. Cutaneous Leishmaniasis: A 2022 Updated Narrative Review into Diagnosis and Management Developments. Am J Clin Dermatol. 2022;23(6):823-840. doi:10.1007/s40257-022-00726-8","Burza S, Croft SL, Boelaert M. Leishmaniasis. Lancet. 2018;392(10151):951-970. doi:10.1016/S0140-6736(18)31204-2"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43865"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14760"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43865"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-31T18:40:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T18:41:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7451"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58449"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":